<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-759-168  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 759 168.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Transactions on Robotics and Automation  August 1989 v5 n4p460(12).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Integration of active and passive sensing techniques forrepresenting three-dimensional objects. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wang, Y.F.; Aggarwal, J.K.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>New algorithms are developed for extracting the shape ofthree-dimensional objects from two-dimensional image data gatheredby both active and passive sensing from multiple viewingdirections.andP;  The determination of 3D object shape from 2D data isa common but serious problem in computer vision.andP;  The methodologyuses projected stripe coding to determine visible surfaceorientation and partial structure from multiple views.andP;  Aninteractive construction/orientation process relates the observedstripe patterns to surface orientations and contours in space.andP;  Abounding volume description is developed and refined from themultiple views.andP;  The approach is computationally efficient.andP;  Thealgorithms are flexible, adaptive, and suitable for use in dynamicenvironments.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     AlgorithmsThree-Dimensional GraphicsObject RecognitionNew Technique.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   System configuration in the single-view algorithm. (chart)Construction of the initial bounding volume structure. (chart)Surface construction process. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>